     1	# Internal System Comparison
     2	
     3	Date: 2026-04-11
     4	Revised: 2026-04-11 (sdk-audit-and-traits-alignment-plan — implementation status added; workforce persona vs traits distinction made explicit)
     5	
     6	## Purpose
     7	
     8	Compare current internal systems to identify the assistant-runtime capabilities that should become shared SDK packages.
     9	
    10	## Implementation Status as of 2026-04-11
    11	
    12	Six packages are implemented and passing tests. This table reflects the current state of extraction:
    13	
    14	| Signal source | Packages it justified | Implemented? |
    15	| --- | --- | --- |
    16	| MSD session/surface design | `sessions`, `surfaces`, `core` | Yes — 31/25/28 tests passing |
    17	| NightCTO orchestration | `coordination`, `connectivity` | Yes — 39/30 tests passing |
    18	| Workforce routing model | `routing` | Yes — 12 tests (DoD gap; not yet production-ready) |
    19	| Sage memory/proactive patterns | `memory`, `proactive` | No — planned v1.1/v1.2 |
    20	| Sage + NightCTO identity patterns | `traits` | No — planned v1.2 |
    21	| All products | `policy` | No — planned v2 |
    22	
    23	---
    24	
    25	## Summary Table
    26	
    27	| System | Strongest signal | What should inform this repo | What should stay product- or infra-specific |
    28	| --- | --- | --- | --- |
    29	| Relay foundation | transport and action substrate | normalized message, delivery, session substrate integration points | provider adapters, auth, webhook verification, raw action dispatch |
    30	| Sage | memory and proactive continuity; identity and voice | memory contracts, follow-up engine concepts, stale-session patterns, traits extraction signal | workspace-specific prompt behavior, product heuristics, workforce persona definitions |
    31	| MSD | session and multi-surface convergence | assistant session model, surface attachment rules, runtime composition | review workflows, review tools, PR-specific logic, workforce persona definitions |
    32	| NightCTO | many-agents-one-assistant orchestration; founder-facing identity | coordination contracts, policy hooks, per-client continuity patterns, traits extraction signal | founder-facing product behavior, specialist lineup, service policy, workforce persona definitions |
    33	| Workforce | routing, persona tiers, and budget envelopes | assistant-facing routing contracts, latency/depth/cost policy, quality-preserving tier selection | persona library, persona definitions, tier names — stay in Workforce |
    34	
    35	---
    36	
    37	## Workforce Persona vs. Assistant Traits
    38	
    39	This is the most important boundary to understand before building against this SDK.
    40	
    41	**Workforce personas** are runtime execution profiles (model, harness, system prompt, service tier). They are defined and owned in Workforce infrastructure. They answer: "What runtime configuration should this agent use to execute a task?"
    42	
    43	**Assistant traits** are identity and behavioral characteristics (voice, style, vocabulary, proactivity, risk posture). They will live in `@relay-assistant/traits` when extracted. They answer: "How should this assistant present itself and behave across interactions?"
    44	
    45	A workforce persona's `systemPrompt` may embed trait values, but the prompt is a persona artifact. Traits are the source data. Products compose traits into personas, not the other way around.
    46	
    47	See [traits-and-persona-layer.md](../architecture/traits-and-persona-layer.md) for the full boundary definition.
    48	
    49	---
    50	
    51	## Relay Foundation
    52	
    53	Relay already appears to own the substrate this repo should build on:
    54	
    55	- transport adapters
    56	- inbound normalization
    57	- outbound delivery
    58	- auth and connection wiring
    59	- scheduler substrate
    60	- low-level action dispatch
    61	
    62	Implication:
    63	
    64	- this repo should compose with Relay
    65	- this repo should not recreate transport infrastructure
    66	
    67	---
    68	
    69	## Sage
    70	
    71	Sage contributes the strongest memory and proactive signals:
    72	
    73	- persistent conversation or workspace continuity
    74	- memory load and save behavior
    75	- follow-up and stale-thread thinking
    76	- context-aware reminders
    77	
    78	Sage also contributes the clearest identity signal for `@relay-assistant/traits` extraction:
    79	
    80	- concise, knowledge-focused communication style
    81	- workspace-specific vocabulary and framing
    82	- medium proactivity level
    83	
    84	Implication:
    85	
    86	- memory and proactive packages are justified
    87	- those packages should capture general contracts, not Sage's exact product behavior
    88	- Sage's local trait object is a primary extraction signal for `@relay-assistant/traits` at v1.2
    89	- Sage's workforce persona definitions stay in Sage/Workforce — they are not SDK concerns
    90	
    91	---
    92	
    93	## MSD
    94	
    95	MSD contributes the strongest session and surface signals:
    96	
    97	- one assistant experience across multiple surfaces
    98	- shared session semantics
    99	- orchestrator or runtime assignment concepts
   100	- strong need for policy around external review actions
   101	
   102	Implication:
   103	
   104	- `sessions` and `surfaces` should be first-class packages
   105	- `core` and `policy` should support multi-surface runtime composition without being review-specific
   106	- MSD's workforce persona definitions stay in Workforce
   107	
   108	---
   109	
   110	## NightCTO
   111	
   112	NightCTO contributes the strongest coordination signals:
   113	
   114	- multiple internal specialists behind one assistant face
   115	- per-client continuity and persistence
   116	- proactive monitoring behavior
   117	- need for governance and auditability
   118	
   119	NightCTO also contributes a strong identity signal for traits extraction:
   120	
   121	- founder/CTO communication register
   122	- high-stakes risk posture
   123	- client-specific vocabulary and framing
   124	
   125	Implication:
   126	
   127	- `coordination`, `policy`, `memory`, and `proactive` are all justified
   128	- the many-agents-one-assistant model is not hypothetical; it already has a clear internal use case
   129	- NightCTO's local trait object is a primary extraction signal for `@relay-assistant/traits` alongside Sage
   130	- NightCTO's workforce personas and service-tier policy stay in Workforce
   131	
   132	---
   133	
   134	## Cross-System Synthesis
   135	
   136	Across the internal systems, the same assistant concerns keep recurring:
   137	
   138	- continuity over time
   139	- continuity across surfaces
   140	- proactive behavior
   141	- coordinated specialists
   142	- focused internal connectivity
   143	- policy around external actions
   144	- consistent identity and behavioral voice across sessions and surfaces
   145	
   146	This is enough evidence to justify a dedicated assistant SDK layer and a dedicated traits layer.
   147	
   148	---
   149	
   150	## Overlap And Tension Analysis
   151	
   152	### Sage vs NightCTO on memory
   153	
   154	Sage's memory signals emphasize conversation continuity, workspace context retention, and proactive follow-up evidence. NightCTO's memory signals emphasize per-client continuity, specialist context, and durable service relationships.
   155	
   156	Shared implication:
   157	- a future `MemoryStore` interface must support more than one scope shape
   158	- the memory layer cannot assume that every durable object is just a chat thread
   159	- the likely shared scopes are user, session, workspace, org, and object/client
   160	
   161	### MSD vs Sage on sessions and surfaces
   162	
   163	MSD's strongest contribution is shared session convergence across multiple surfaces. Sage currently shows more product-specific memory and proactive behavior, but its runtime still implies the need for consistent session continuity when the assistant appears in multiple places.
   164	
   165	Shared implication:
   166	- the session layer should treat surfaces as attachments to one assistant session rather than as the primary continuity object
   167	- that abstraction is likely reusable across both product styles
   168	
   169	### NightCTO vs MSD on coordination
   170	
   171	NightCTO makes the specialist pattern explicit through registry, dispatch, triage, and proactive flows. MSD's architecture implies orchestrator/notifier/reviewer roles and multi-surface runtime composition.
   172	
   173	Shared implication:
   174	- coordination should be separated from domain-specific specialist lineups
   175	- both products need many-agents-one-assistant semantics even though their domains differ
   176	
   177	### Why connectivity deserves its own package
   178	
   179	The internal systems do not merely need transport; they need efficient communication between sophisticated subsystems.
   180	
   181	This communication is not generic chatter. It needs to be:
   182	- low-latency
   183	- selective
   184	- high-signal
   185	- oriented toward convergence
   186	- able to carry attention, uncertainty, escalation, and synthesis cues
   187	
   188	That is why a distinct `@relay-assistant/connectivity` package is justified above Relay transport and alongside coordination.
   189	
   190	### Why traits deserve their own package
   191	
   192	Sage, MSD, and NightCTO all have product-local patterns for how their assistants present themselves. The field shapes overlap (voice, formality, proactivity, risk posture). Extracting these into a shared `@relay-assistant/traits` package is justified when two or more products have defined local trait objects with overlapping shapes.
   193	
   194	The extraction should not happen before those patterns exist in the products. Define local trait objects first; extract when there is concrete overlap to generalize.
   195	
   196	---
   197	
   198	## Boundary Conclusion
   199	
   200	The right separation is:
   201	
   202	- Relay foundation for transport and substrate
   203	- `relay-agent-assistant` for shared assistant runtime contracts and identity traits
   204	- Workforce for runtime execution profiles (personas, tiers, model selection)
   205	- product repos for domain behavior, product-specific persona definitions, and product policy
   206	
   207	That separation is consistent with all three product directions and does not require cloud-specific assumptions.
   208	
   209	---
   210	
   211	## Workforce
   212	
   213	Workforce contributes the strongest routing and token-budgeting signals:
   214	
   215	- intent to persona selection
   216	- tiered runtimes (`minimum`, `best-value`, `best`)
   217	- explicit depth/latency/cost envelopes
   218	- routing profiles that preserve quality while changing operating envelope
   219	
   220	Implication:
   221	
   222	- `routing` should be a first-class assistant-sdk package
   223	- the assistant SDK should align with workforce workload-router concepts instead of inventing a divergent model-choice layer
   224	- latency and cost policy should be explicit runtime concerns rather than ad hoc product logic
   225	- SDK routing modes (`cheap`/`fast`/`deep`) are SDK vocabulary; workforce tier names (`minimum`/`best-value`/`best`) stay in Workforce; products map between them
   226	- workforce persona definitions remain Workforce-owned and are not imported into this SDK

