   120	
   121	## Package Responsibilities
   122	
   123	### `@relay-assistant/core`
   124	
   125	**Implementation status: IMPLEMENTED — 31 tests passing, `SPEC_RECONCILED`**
   126	
   127	Owns:
   128	
   129	- `createAssistant()` and assistant definition types
   130	- runtime lifecycle and capability registration
   131	- assistant identity fields: `id`, `name`, `description?`
   132	- lightweight composition entrypoints and shared cross-package types
   133	
   134	Identity scope note:
   135	- `core` owns `id`, `name`, `description?` — the minimum identity fields needed to run an assistant
   136	- Behavioral identity (voice, style, vocabulary, proactivity) will live in `@relay-assistant/traits` when extracted
   137	- `AssistantDefinition` does **not** have a `traits` field yet. When `@relay-assistant/traits` ships, a `traits?: TraitsProvider` optional field will be added. Do not add it prematurely — the current types.ts has no such field and that is correct.
   138	
   139	Composition note:
   140	- `core` should not become a heavy package that hard-depends on every other package by default
   141	- prefer interface-first composition and optional package wiring so consumers can adopt only the packages they need
   142	
   143	Must not own:
   144	
   145	- provider-specific transport code
   146	- memory backend implementation details
   147	- product workflows
   148	- workforce persona definitions
   149	
   150	### `@relay-assistant/traits` (planned — v1.2)
   151	
   152	**Implementation status: NOT IMPLEMENTED — no spec, no types, no placeholder**
   153	
   154	Owns:
   155	
   156	- `AssistantTraits` type definition (voice, style, vocabulary, proactivity level, risk posture, formality, domain framing)
   157	- `SurfaceFormattingTraits` type definition (per-surface-type formatting preferences that inform format hooks)
   158	- `TraitsProvider` interface — a read-only accessor that packages can consume without hard-depending on traits
   159	- `createTraitsProvider(traits: AssistantTraits)` factory
   160	- Validation that trait values are within acceptable ranges/enums
   161	
   162	Must not own:
   163	
   164	- Persona definitions — those stay in workforce
   165	- System prompts — those are persona artifacts, not traits
   166	- Product-specific behavioral logic — stays in product repos
   167	- Model selection or routing — stays in `routing`
   168	- Memory or session state — stays in those packages
   169	
   170	Dependency direction: traits has zero upstream dependencies on other SDK packages. It is a leaf data package.
   171	
   172	See [traits-and-persona-layer.md](traits-and-persona-layer.md) for full spec.
   173	
   174	### `@relay-assistant/memory`
   175	
   176	**Implementation status: placeholder — spec exists (`v1-memory-spec.md`, `IMPLEMENTATION_READY`); roadmap: v1.1**
   177	
   178	Implementation posture:
   179	
   180	- first investigate and reuse the existing `@agent-relay/memory` package where possible
   181	- prefer an assistant-facing adapter/composition layer over a greenfield memory engine
   182	- only add new memory runtime logic here when assistant-specific requirements are not already satisfied by Relay memory capabilities
   183	
   184	Owns:
   185	
   186	- memory scopes such as user, session, workspace, org, and object
   187	- retrieval, write, compaction, and promotion contracts
   188	- memory adapter interfaces for future backends
   189	
   190	Must not own:
   191	
   192	- one product's tag taxonomy
   193	- one surface's thread model as the only memory key shape
   194	
   195	### `@relay-assistant/proactive`
   196	
   197	**Implementation status: placeholder — no formal spec; roadmap: v1.2**
   198	
   199	Owns:
   200	
   201	- follow-up engines
   202	- watcher definitions
   203	- reminder policies
   204	- scheduler bindings over Relay substrate
   205	- evidence contracts for stale-session or follow-up decisions
   206	
   207	Must not own:
   208	
   209	- product-only trigger logic
   210	- surface-specific evidence collection that cannot generalize
   211	
   212	### `@relay-assistant/sessions`
   213	
   214	**Implementation status: IMPLEMENTED — 25 tests passing, `IMPLEMENTATION_READY`**
   215	
   216	Owns:
   217	
   218	- assistant session identity
   219	- attachment of multiple surfaces to one assistant session
   220	- resume, reattach, and affinity rules
   221	- scoping rules across user, workspace, org, and object contexts
   222	
   223	Must not own:
   224	
   225	- raw transport sessions
   226	- provider webhook semantics
   227	
   228	### `@relay-assistant/surfaces`
   229	
   230	**Implementation status: IMPLEMENTED — 28 tests passing, `SPEC_RECONCILED`**
   231	
   232	Owns:
   233	
   234	- assistant-facing inbound and outbound abstractions
   235	- assistant-layer fanout policy describing which connected surfaces should receive a given assistant response
   236	- formatter and capability hooks above Relay normalization
   237	- surface metadata such as threading or attachment support
   238	
   239	Fanout boundary note:
   240	- Relay foundation still owns actual transport delivery to each destination
   241	- `surfaces` only decides assistant-level targeting and formatting across attached surfaces
   242	- Example: deciding that one assistant summary should go to web plus Slack belongs here; the actual Slack API post and web transport delivery remain in Relay foundation
   243	
   244	Must not own:
   245	
   246	- webhook verification
   247	- provider SDK clients as foundational transport code
